{"title_page": "Howard Burnham", "text_new": "{{Infobox spy \n| name = Mather Howard Burnham\n| nickname =\n| image = Mather howard burnham 1915.jpg\n| caption = M. Howard Burnham, 1915\n| allegiance = [[United States]], [[France]]\n| service =\n| serviceyears =[[World War I]] \n| rank = \n| operation =\n| award = \n| codename1 =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1870|05|27}}\n| birth_place = Tivoli, [[Minnesota]] (near [[Mankato, Minnesota|Mankato]]), United States\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1917|05|04|1870|05|27}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], US\n| buried = New York City, New York \n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| nationality = American\n| residence = \n| parents = Rev [[Edwin Otway Burnham]]<br />Rebecca Russell Burnham\n| spouse = {{ubl|Margaret|Constance Newton (Connie)}}\n| children = 4\n| occupation = [[Mining engineer]], [[Spy]]<ref name=\"chances\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |authorlink=Frederick Russell Burnham |title=Taking Chances |publisher=Haynes Corp |year=1944 |location=|pages=217\u2013232 |isbn= 1-879356-32-5 |nopp=true}}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Michigan Technological University]]\n| signature = \n}}\n\n'''Mather Howard Burnham''' (May 27, 1870 \u2013 May 4, 1917),<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Report of Death of American Citizens Abroad, no. 554, dated May 11, 1917, American Consulate, Nice, France.</ref> was an American who  went by the name of Howard; his brother was the celebrated scout [[Frederick Russell Burnham]]. He traveled the world, frequently worked as a [[mining engineer]] and, during [[World War I]], he became an [[intelligence officer]] and [[spy]] for the government of [[France]].<ref name=\"chances\"/> He had a wooden leg which he used to conceal tools for spying when he was behind enemy lines.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:R e burnham clapp.gif|left|thumb|100px|Rebecca Russell Burnham, mother]]\nBurnham was born to a [[missionary]] family on a [[Sioux]] Indian reservation in Tivoli, [[Minnesota]] (near [[Mankato, Minnesota|Mankato]]), just before his family moved to [[Los Angeles, California]]. He was named after his cousin Lieutenant [[Howard Mather Burnham]], a United States Army [[American Civil War|Civil War]] officer who was killed in action in the [[Battle of Chickamauga]].  His father, the Rev. [[Edwin Otway Burnham]] of [[Kentucky]], a long time [[frontiersman]] and missionary died when Burnham was only 3, leaving the family destitute. He and his mother, Rebecca (Elizabeth) Russell Burnham, originally from [[Westminster]], [[Middlesex]], [[England]], left to live with an Uncle in [[Iowa]], but his brother Fred, then 12, stayed in California to repay the family debts and to make his own way.<ref name=\"scouting\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |authorlink=Frederick Russell Burnham |title=Scouting on Two Continents |publisher=Doubleday, Page & company |year=1926 |location= |pages= |oclc=407686 }}</ref><ref name=\"lott1981\">{{cite book |last=Lott | first=Jack | authorlink= Jack Lott |editor-first=Craig | editor-last=Boddington |title=America \u2013 The Men and Their Guns That Made Her Great |publisher=Petersen Publishing Co. |year=1981 |pages=77\u201391 |chapter=Chapter 8.  The Making of a Hero: Burnham in the Tonto Basin |isbn=0-8227-3022-7}}</ref>\n \nAt 14, Burnham was in school in [[Massachusetts]].  Ill with an injured leg, his brother sent him the money to return to Los Angeles.  His leg was removed four inches below the knee.  He also suffered from [[tuberculosis]] and following the amputation he had a long convalescence.  For those two years he lived with his brother who taught him how to shoot, saddle a horse and pack animal, the art of [[scoutcraft]] and  how to ride the range, and all of this in spite of his wooden leg.  A voracious reader with an amazing memory, he enjoyed books on military strategies and tactics, and was fascinated by history, [[geology]], [[metallurgy]], and mining.  He roamed the deserts from [[Death Valley]] to lower California, living among and learning from the [[Cahuilla]] Indians of Agua Caliente (now [[Palm Springs, California]]), and teaming up at times with solitary prospectors to learn desert prospecting, pocket hunting, and the mysteries of the \"great horn spoon\" (probably the [[California Gold Rush]]).<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\nIn 1888, during one of his desert prospecting excursions, Burnham had a shoot-out with an Indian (not Cahuilla).<ref name=\"chances\"/> He was on an old trail leading over the mountains between [[Kawia]] and [[San Jacinto, California|San Jacinto]] and less than an hour before the attack he met an Indian with whom he had a conversation in Spanish.  Burnham continued on the trail until he heard a slight report and felt something hit his right leg, and then a second report resulting in a flesh wound to his left leg.  He immediately threw himself flat on the ground and commenced cautiously eyeing the surrounding country for the enemy.  When saw a hat rising from behind a rock about 150 yards away, he drew his pistol and fired on the hat.  His enemy fled down the Los Coyotes creek, down the canyon trail Burnham had been following, with the intent to assume a new ambush.  Burnham recognized his enemy as the Indian he had met a short time earlier and he knew that this Indian was carrying a Winchester rifle and had him out-gunned.  Burnham left his pack animal, tools, provisions and blankets and quickly fled on his horse down a steep cliff away from the trail and to safety in San Jacinto.<ref name=\"sfchronicle25jun1888\">{{cite news |title= Indian Raiders: Southern California not yet exempt from them |newspaper= [[San Francisco Chronicle]] |location=[[San Francisco, California]] |issn= 1932-8672 |date=June 25, 1888|page=8}}</ref>\n\nFor the next few years, Burnham studied mining and worked on and off in the California desert as mining engineer at the [[Alvord mine]], a gold mine owned and operated by the Burnham-Clapp family and their Pasadena business partners 1885\u20131891.<ref name=\"vanwyk\">{{cite book |last=van Wyke |first=Peter |title=Burnham: Chief of Scouts |publisher=Trafford Publishing|year=2003 |location=Victoria, Canada |pages=38, 168 |isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes8sep1891\">{{cite news |title= Pasadena; Personal |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date=September 8, 1891|page=7 |quote=Howard Burnham will return to the Alvord mine today.}}</ref><ref name=\"alvordmine\">{{cite web |url= http://mojavedesert.net/desert-fever/alvord.html |title=Alvord Mine |accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"familyletters\">{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=Mary E |author2=Richard H Bradford |title=An American family on the African frontier: the Burnham family letters, 1893\u20131896 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart|year=1993 |location=Niwot, Colorado |page=7 |isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}</ref> He received his professional mining certification from the Pacific Chemical Works of San Francisco, an assay company owned and operated by [[Henry Garber Hanks]], the first State Mineralogist for California.<ref name=\"miningcert\">{{cite news |title= Pacific Chemical Works mining certificate |location=[[San Francisco]] |date=July 7, 1890 |quote= certification to assay gold, silver, lead, tin, and mercury, and the determination of minerals and the use of blacopipe.}}</ref><ref name=\"stategeologists\">{{cite web |url=http://www.consrv.ca.gov/cgs/cgs_history |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090430000640/http://www.consrv.ca.gov/cgs/cgs_history |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 30, 2009 |title=California Geological Survey \u2013 State Geologists |accessdate=February 1, 2010 |quote=Henry Garber Hanks State Mineralogist 1880\u20131886.  Hanks started his own assaying company, Pacific Chemical Works, while in San Francisco. }}</ref>\n\n== South Africa and Rhodesia ==\nAfter the Alvord mine in California was destroyed in a fire, Burnham stayed in California until 1894 to wrap up his family's affairs with the mine and left for the [[South African Republic]] as soon as he could to join his brother Fred already in [[Bulawayo|Bulawayo, Matabeleland]].<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> He soon found work as a mining engineer and was in charge of the assay laboratory and smelting room at the Langlaagte Royal Mine in the [[South African Republic|Transvaal]].<ref name=\"flemming1903\">{{cite journal |author=John Flemming |date=April 1903 |title=The extraction of gold from cyanide house slimes by a wet method |journal=Journal of the South African Institute of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=3 |issue= |page=347}}</ref><ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\">{{cite news |title= Nearly Hanged on charge of spying; Unpleasant predicament of Howard Burnham, a Californian, in South Africa |newspaper= [[San Francisco Call]] |location=[[San Francisco, California]] |issn= 1941-0719 |date= Jan 17, 1900 |page=2 }}</ref> In 1895, he was preparing to accompany his brother in a massive expedition into [[Northern Rhodesia]] when he took ill and was forced to leave for Europe to recuperate.<ref name=\"latimes8jun1895\">{{cite news |title= Southern California News; Pasadena Brevities |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Jun 8, 1895|page=11 }}</ref><ref name=\"times9may1899\">{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=May 9, 1899 |title=Railway And Other Companies: Northern Territories (B.S.A.) Exploring Company Limited |journal=[[The Times]] |page=3 |issue=35824}}</ref> He left for [[German Empire|Germany]] accompanied by his nephew Roderick, and the two of them then went to [[London, England]].<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> In 1895, he married his first wife Margaret.<ref name=\"familyletters\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Application for emergency passport, U.S. Consulate at Johannesburg, Republic of South Africa, 29 September 1899</ref> He returned to the United States and from 1896-1898 attended the Michigan Mining School (now [[Michigan Technological University]]), graduating with an S.B.<ref name=\"michigan1898\">{{cite book |title=Catalog of the Michigan College of Mines (1896-1898) |last= |first= |authorlink= |date=August 1898 |publisher=Published by the College |location=Houghton, Michigan |isbn= |pages=175, 179}}</ref> By September 1898, he and his wife were back in Africa and he was working for an English syndicate and supervising over 2,000 miners at the Rosa deep gold mine near [[Johannesburg, South Africa]].<ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"latimes18nov1899\">{{cite news |title= Southern California by Towns and Counties; In South Africa |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Nov 18, 1899 |page=15 |quote= Howard Burnham of this city has been for a year or more the engineer of a gold mine near Johannesburg, South Africa and his wife has been with him.  Mrs. Burnham retreated to Cape Town at the start of the Second Boer War, but Howard remained at his post in the mines, protected by his American citizenship.}}</ref> While in the Transvaal, Burnham was a chief chemist, an engineer, and an assistant inspector for mines, and he wrote a textbook: ''Modern Mine Valuation''.<ref name=\"howardburnham\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=M. Howard |authorlink=Howard Burnham |title=Modern Mine Valuation |url=https://archive.org/details/modernminevaluat00burnuoft |publisher=London, C. Griffin and Company, limited |year=1912 |isbn= 1-151-74631-2}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Second Boer War]] broke out in 1899, Burnham felt he would be protected because of his American citizenship. Initially he remained at his post in the mines in the Boer Republic, but as a precaution he sent his wife to [[Cape Town, South Africa]], then a British colony.<ref name=\"latimes18nov1899\"/> But the situation in Johannesburg quickly worsened.  The Boers seized the mine and began working it for their own benefit.  Burnham traveled to [[East London, South Africa]] to inform the syndicate directors of the situation.  He was captured by the British and held 24 hrs before he could prove that he was an American citizen.  When he started back to Johannesburg, he was captured by the Boers who took him for a British spy.  For a time he was uncertain if he would be shot or hanged. He wired his family for funds to help get him out of his predicament.<ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\"/><ref name=\"latimes17nov1900\">{{cite news |title= Southern California by Towns and Counties; A Pasadenan in Africa |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Jan 17, 1900 |page=I15 }}</ref> Only weeks earlier, his brother had been prospecting in [[Alaska]] during the [[Klondike Gold Rush]] when he received a telegram from [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Lord Roberts]] requesting his assistance in the war \u2013 Fred left for Africa within the hour.<ref name=\"americanheritage\">{{cite journal |author=Byron Farwell |authorlink=Byron Farwell |date=March 1976 |title=Taking Sides in the Boer War |journal=American Heritage Magazine |volume=20 |issue=3 |issn=0002-8738 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1976/3/1976_3_20.shtml |accessdate=2010-02-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107112133/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1976/3/1976_3_20.shtml |archivedate=2009-01-07 }}</ref> Fred Burnham had just been appointed Chief of Scouts for the [[British Army]] and was en route to South Africa via England, but he was still too distant to provide any immediate help.<ref name=\"scouting\"/>\n\nOver the next few years, he lived in both England and South Africa. He gave lectures and contributed a series of articles on mining techniques and the sundry principles underlying the finance of mining enterprises, more especially the \"risk rate.\"  In London on November 18, 1903, Burnham married Constance Newton, then a young school teacher and an heiress to [[Newton, Chambers & Company]], whom he had met on the ship during their voyage to South Africa.<ref>Marriage certificate, from Holly Trinity Church, Brompton Parish, London, 18th November 1903, column no. 118</ref> From 1905 until about 1908, Burnham was a non-resident fellow at the Royal Colonial Institute in London.<ref name=\"royalcolinst\">{{cite journal |author= |year=1908 |title=List of Fellows |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Colonial Institute |volume=39 |issue= |page=401}}</ref>\n\n== Mexico ==\n[[File:Burnham closeup 1900.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Maj [[Frederick Russell Burnham]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], brother]]\nWhile his wife and children stayed in England and France, Burnham returned to North America in 1907 and for the next few years became associated with the [[Yaqui River]] irrigation project in [[Mexico]] with his brother Fred.<ref name=\"scouting\"/> In 1908, he and W. A. Wadham of London, England, took a month-long geology and mining trip through Sonora on behalf of American and English business partners.<ref name=\"mining18july1908\">{{cite journal |journal=Mining and Engineering World |date=July 18, 1908 |volume=29 |issue= |page=110 |issn=0096-4840}}</ref> Negotiations were made for the purchase of four properties: the Batue, Mequite, La Fiera, and another property.  He considered the La Fiera to be the best of the lot and a small force of men under the supervision of John Anderson was put to work there.<ref name=\"mining18july1908\"/> In 1909, he traveled with Hector Walker of England on a 300-mile journey from [[Phoenix, Arizona]] into Mexico, and then east through [[Chihuahua, Chihuahua|Chihuahua]] and into the Sierra Madres to look for good grazing lands and minerals.<ref name=\"bisbeedailyreview_11sep1909\">{{cite news |title= Plan Extended Horseback Journal |newspaper= [[Bisbee Daily Review]] |location=[[Bisbee, Arizona]] |issn= 2158-4788 |date=Sep 11, 1909|page=1}}</ref>  His brother purchased water rights and some {{convert|300|acre|km2}} of land in this region and contacted an old friend of the Burnhams from Africa, [[John Hays Hammond]], who conducted his own studies and then purchased an additional {{convert|900000|acre|km2}} of this land\u2014an area the size of [[Rhode Island]].  Just as the irrigation and mining projects were nearing completion in 1912, a long series of [[Mexican Revolution|Mexican revolutions]] began.  The final blow to Burnham-Hammond plans came in 1917 when Mexico passed laws prohibiting the sale of land to foreigners. The Burnham and the Hammond families carried their properties until 1930 and then sold them to the Mexican government.<ref name=\"hammond\">{{cite book |author=[[John Hays Hammond]] |title=The Autobiography of John Hays Hammond |url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofj0001hamm |url-access=registration |publisher=Farrar & Rinehart|year=1935 |isbn= 0-405-05913-2 |page=565}}</ref>\n\n== World War I Espionage ==\nDuring [[World War I]], Burnham worked in intelligence for [[France]]. In 1914, he was incarcerated near [[Tampico, Mexico]] as a suspected spy, and was released with the help of [[William Jennings Bryan]], the U.S. Secretary of State.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">Mather Howard Burnham U.S. passport application affidavit/identifying documents, U.S. consulate, Barcelona, Spain, 26 February 1915</ref> He immediately left Mexico for France and stopped in [[Barcelona, Spain]] on his way to [[Algiers, Algeria]], then a French colony that the German Intelligence had infiltrated to support of the rebels.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> He was sent on a dangerous mission to lead 28 soldiers into the desert, meet with the rebels, and persuade them to make peace with the French.  On the way, the group encountered a hostile clan, lost 20 men, exhausted all of their ammunition, and were taken prisoner. All were executed, except Burnham. A sheik elder with the clan had earlier gotten into trouble with the French in Algiers and Burnham had come to his defense, leading to the release of the man.  Burnham returned to Algiers alone and was then sent to France.<ref name=\"chances\"/> \n \nIn 1917, [[List of intelligence agencies of France|French intelligence]] then sent Burnham across enemy lines as a spy to discover if the Germans were preparing a new front through the [[Alps]]. Traveling through neutral [[Switzerland]], Burnham assumed his former identity as an American mining engineer and crossed into Germany on the plea of extreme ill-health \u2013 his tuberculosis had violently resurfaced. Burnham had spent much time before the war in German spas, and his work for the French intelligence had been classified, so the real reason for his near-death return was not suspected by the authorities. Additionally, he was traveling with large quantities of American gold coins for his treatment and gold was desperately needed in wartime Germany. Nevertheless, Burnham was both searched and closely watched throughout his stay.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n \nWhile in Germany, Burnham applied his engineering skills to converting simple household materials in useful surveying instruments, and he used his wooden leg to conceal these tools when he traveled to places such as [[Bad Nauheim]]. Due to the high cost of his treatments, $500 a month paid in gold, Burnham was a welcome visitor at every resort in Germany.  Still, all of his correspondence was reviewed and at the insistence of German authorities he was frequently escorted by one or more nurses and a private secretary. Since he was unable to permanently record his surveys and other findings on paper, he relied on his remarkable memory.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n \nBurnham became very ill and was allowed to return to Switzerland for his health. The French government quickly transported Burnham to [[Cannes, France]]. From his death bed, Burnham shared his secrets with other intelligence officers and the French government transported his family from England to Cannes. The data Burnham had gathered was convincing: the Germans were not opening a new front in Alps and there was no need to move allied troops away from the Western Front.  His dying words he whispered to his surgeon: \"Always have I wanted to help pay the debt my country has owed to France. Go back to the front and save the living.  I am already dead.\" He was buried in Cannes beside the tomb of [[A. Kingsley Macomber]], another American, to honor the French Admiral [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Paul de Grasse]] whose fleet had enabled [[George Washington]] to force the surrender of [[Lord Cornwallis]] at [[Yorktown, Virginia]] in 1781.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Fhcbabyfred.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Frederick Russell Burnham, M. Howard Burnham, Connie Burnham, and baby Fred, c1904]]\nBurnham was a descendant of [[Thomas Burnham]] (1617\u20131688) of [[Hartford, Connecticut]], the first American ancestor of a large number of Burnhams.<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> The descendants of Thomas Burnham have been noted in every American war, including the [[French and Indian war]].<ref name=\"pressreflib\">{{cite book |title =Press Reference Library: Notables of the West |publisher =International News Service |location=New York|year =1915 |oclc=5532411}}</ref>\n \nHe had four children:\n* Frederick Newton Burnham (Aug 25, 1904\u20131959), b. [[Lydenburg]], [[Republic of South Africa]] (now the Territory of South Africa). d. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n* Thomas Chambers Burnham (May 14, 1906 \u2013 2004), b. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]; d. [[Key Largo, Florida]].\n* Mary Burnham (May 29, 1909 \u2013 1987), b. [[Key Largo]], [[Florida]]; d. [[London, Connecticut]]\n* Katherine \"Kitty\" Burnham (October 9, 1911 \u2013 1999), b. [[San Francisco]], [[California]]; d. [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Works===\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |year=1901 |title=Continuous Section System Mine Sampling |journal=Transactions of the Institution of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=X |issue= |pages=204\u2013218 |issn=0371-7836}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |year=1904 |title=Treatment of Telluride Ores by Dry Crushing and Roasting at Kalgoorlie |journal=Transactions of the Institution of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=XIII |issue= |page=59 |issn=0371-7836}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |date=June 1911 |title=Financing a Mine |journal=Mining Magazine |volume= |issue= |pages=445 |issn=0308-6631 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=M. Howard |title=Modern Mine Valuation |url=https://archive.org/details/modernminevaluat00burnrich |publisher=London, C. Griffin and Company, limited |year=1912 |isbn= 1-151-74631-2}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=Mary E |author2=Richard H Bradford |title=An American family on the African frontier: the Burnham family letters, 1893\u20131896 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart|year=1993 |location=Niwot, Colorado|isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}  Some Burnham correspondence between 1893-1896.\n\n===Biographies===\n*{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |title=Taking Chances |publisher=Haynes |year=1944 |isbn= 1-879356-32-5}}.  Chapter XXXI is on M. Howard Burnham.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burnham, Mather Howard}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:American explorers]]\n[[Category:French spies]]\n[[Category:People from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:American mining businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American mining engineers]]\n[[Category:South African mining engineers]]\n[[Category:World War I spies for France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Michigan Technological University alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:19th-century South African engineers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox spy \n| name = Mather Howard Burnham\n| nickname =\n| image = Mather howard burnham 1915.jpg\n| caption = M. Howard Burnham, 1915\n| allegiance = [[United States]], [[France]]\n| service =\n| serviceyears =[[World War I]] \n| rank = \n| operation =\n| award = \n| codename1 =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1870|05|27}}\n| birth_place = Tivoli, [[Minnesota]] (near [[Mankato, Minnesota|Mankato]]), United States\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1917|05|04|1870|05|27}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], US\n| buried = New York City, New York \n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| nationality = American\n| residence = \n| parents = Rev [[Edwin Otway Burnham]]<br />Rebecca Russell Burnham\n| spouse = {{ubl|Margaret|Constance Newton (Connie)}}\n| children = 4\n| occupation = [[Mining engineer]], [[Spy]]<ref name=\"chances\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |authorlink=Frederick Russell Burnham |title=Taking Chances |publisher=Haynes Corp |year=1944 |location=|pages=217\u2013232 |isbn= 1-879356-32-5 |nopp=true}}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Michigan Technological University]]\n| signature = \n}}\n\n'''Mather Howard Burnham''' (May 27, 1870 \u2013 May 4, 1917),<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Report of Death of American Citizens Abroad, no. 554, dated May 11, 1917, American Consulate, Nice, France.</ref> was an American who  went by the name of Howard; his brother was the celebrated scout [[Frederick Russell Burnham]]. He traveled the world, frequently worked as a [[mining engineer]] and, during [[World War I]], he became an [[intelligence officer]] and [[spy]] for the government of [[France]].<ref name=\"chances\"/> He had a wooden leg which he used to conceal tools for spying when he was behind enemy lines.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:R e burnham clapp.gif|left|thumb|100px|Rebecca Russell Burnham, mother]]\nBurnham was born to a [[missionary]] family on a [[Sioux]] Indian reservation in Tivoli, [[Minnesota]] (near [[Mankato, Minnesota|Mankato]]), just before his family moved to [[Los Angeles, California]]. He was named after his cousin Lieutenant [[Howard Mather Burnham]], a United States Army [[American Civil War|Civil War]] officer who was killed in action in the [[Battle of Chickamauga]].  His father, the Rev. [[Edwin Otway Burnham]] of [[Kentucky]], a long time [[frontiersman]] and missionary died when Burnham was only 3, leaving the family destitute. He and his mother, Rebecca (Elizabeth) Russell Burnham, originally from [[Westminster]], [[Middlesex]], [[England]], left to live with an Uncle in [[Iowa]], but his brother Fred, then 12, stayed in California to repay the family debts and to make his own way.<ref name=\"scouting\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |authorlink=Frederick Russell Burnham |title=Scouting on Two Continents |publisher=Doubleday, Page & company |year=1926 |location= |pages= |oclc=407686 }}</ref><ref name=\"lott1981\">{{cite book |last=Lott | first=Jack | authorlink= Jack Lott |editor-first=Craig | editor-last=Boddington |title=America \u2013 The Men and Their Guns That Made Her Great |publisher=Petersen Publishing Co. |year=1981 |pages=77\u201391 |chapter=Chapter 8.  The Making of a Hero: Burnham in the Tonto Basin |isbn=0-8227-3022-7}}</ref>\n \nAt 14, Burnham was in school in [[Massachusetts]].  Ill with an injured leg, his brother sent him the money to return to Los Angeles.  His leg was removed four inches below the knee.  He also suffered from [[tuberculosis]] and following the amputation he had a long convalescence.  For those two years he lived with his brother who taught him how to shoot, saddle a horse and pack animal, the art of [[scoutcraft]] and  how to ride the range, and all of this in spite of his wooden leg.  A voracious reader with an amazing memory, he enjoyed books on military strategies and tactics, and was fascinated by history, [[geology]], [[metallurgy]], and mining.  He roamed the deserts from [[Death Valley]] to lower California, living among and learning from the [[Cahuilla]] Indians of Agua Caliente (now [[Palm Springs, California]]), and teaming up at times with solitary prospectors to learn desert prospecting, pocket hunting, and the mysteries of the \"great horn spoon\" (probably the [[California Gold Rush]]).<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\nIn 1888, during one of his desert prospecting excursions, Burnham had a shoot-out with an Indian (not Cahuilla).<ref name=\"chances\"/> He was on an old trail leading over the mountains between [[Kawia]] and [[San Jacinto, California|San Jacinto]] and less than an hour before the attack he met an Indian with whom he had a conversation in Spanish.  Burnham continued on the trail until he heard a slight report and felt something hit his right leg, and then a second report resulting in a flesh wound to his left leg.  He immediately threw himself flat on the ground and commenced cautiously eyeing the surrounding country for the enemy.  When saw a hat rising from behind a rock about 150 yards away, he drew his pistol and fired on the hat.  His enemy fled down the Los Coyotes creek, down the canyon trail Burnham had been following, with the intent to assume a new ambush.  Burnham recognized his enemy as the Indian he had met a short time earlier and he knew that this Indian was carrying a Winchester rifle and had him out-gunned.  Burnham left his pack animal, tools, provisions and blankets and quickly fled on his horse down a steep cliff away from the trail and to safety in San Jacinto.<ref name=\"sfchronicle25jun1888\">{{cite news |title= Indian Raiders: Southern California not yet exempt from them |newspaper= [[San Francisco Chronicle]] |location=[[San Francisco, California]] |issn= 1932-8672 |date=June 25, 1888|page=8}}</ref>\n\nFor the next few years, Burnham studied mining and worked on and off in the California desert as mining engineer at the [[Alvord mine]], a gold mine owned and operated by the Burnham-Clapp family and their Pasadena business partners 1885\u20131891.<ref name=\"vanwyk\">{{cite book |last=van Wyke |first=Peter |title=Burnham: Chief of Scouts |publisher=Trafford Publishing|year=2003 |location=Victoria, Canada |pages=38, 168 |isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes8sep1891\">{{cite news |title= Pasadena; Personal |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date=September 8, 1891|page=7 |quote=Howard Burnham will return to the Alvord mine today.}}</ref><ref name=\"alvordmine\">{{cite web |url= http://mojavedesert.net/desert-fever/alvord.html |title=Alvord Mine |accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"familyletters\">{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=Mary E |author2=Richard H Bradford |title=An American family on the African frontier: the Burnham family letters, 1893\u20131896 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart|year=1993 |location=Niwot, Colorado |page=7 |isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}</ref> He received his professional mining certification from the Pacific Chemical Works of San Francisco, an assay company owned and operated by [[Henry Garber Hanks]], the first State Mineralogist for California.<ref name=\"miningcert\">{{cite news |title= Pacific Chemical Works mining certificate |location=[[San Francisco]] |date=July 7, 1890 |quote= certification to assay gold, silver, lead, tin, and mercury, and the determination of minerals and the use of blacopipe.}}</ref><ref name=\"stategeologists\">{{cite web |url=http://www.consrv.ca.gov/cgs/cgs_history |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090430000640/http://www.consrv.ca.gov/cgs/cgs_history |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 30, 2009 |title=California Geological Survey \u2013 State Geologists |accessdate=February 1, 2010 |quote=Henry Garber Hanks State Mineralogist 1880\u20131886.  Hanks started his own assaying company, Pacific Chemical Works, while in San Francisco. }}</ref>\n\n== South Africa and Rhodesia ==\nAfter the Alvord mine in California was destroyed in a fire, Burnham stayed in California until 1894 to wrap up his family's affairs with the mine and left for the [[South African Republic]] as soon as he could to join his brother Fred already in [[Bulawayo|Bulawayo, Matabeleland]].<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> He soon found work as a mining engineer and was in charge of the assay laboratory and smelting room at the Langlaagte Royal Mine in the [[South African Republic|Transvaal]].<ref name=\"flemming1903\">{{cite journal |author=John Flemming |date=April 1903 |title=The extraction of gold from cyanide house slimes by a wet method |journal=Journal of the South African Institute of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=3 |issue= |page=347}}</ref><ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\">{{cite news |title= Nearly Hanged on charge of spying; Unpleasant predicament of Howard Burnham, a Californian, in South Africa |newspaper= [[San Francisco Call]] |location=[[San Francisco, California]] |issn= 1941-0719 |date= Jan 17, 1900 |page=2 }}</ref> In 1895, he was preparing to accompany his brother in a massive expedition into [[Northern Rhodesia]] when he took ill and was forced to leave for Europe to recuperate.<ref name=\"latimes8jun1895\">{{cite news |title= Southern California News; Pasadena Brevities |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Jun 8, 1895|page=11 }}</ref><ref name=\"times9may1899\">{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=May 9, 1899 |title=Railway And Other Companies: Northern Territories (B.S.A.) Exploring Company Limited |journal=[[The Times]] |page=3 |issue=35824}}</ref> He left for [[German Empire|Germany]] accompanied by his nephew Roderick, and the two of them then went to [[London, England]].<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> In 1895, he married his first wife Margaret.<ref name=\"familyletters\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Application for emergency passport, U.S. Consulate at Johannesburg, Republic of South Africa, 29 September 1899</ref> He returned to the United States and from 1896-1898 attended the Michigan Mining School (now [[Michigan Technological University]]), graduating with an S.B.<ref name=\"michigan1898\">{{cite book |title=Catalog of the Michigan College of Mines (1896-1898) |last= |first= |authorlink= |date=August 1898 |publisher=Published by the College |location=Houghton, Michigan |isbn= |pages=175, 179}}</ref> By September 1898, he and his wife were back in Africa and he was working for an English syndicate and supervising over 2,000 miners at the Rosa deep gold mine near [[Johannesburg, South Africa]].<ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"latimes18nov1899\">{{cite news |title= Southern California by Towns and Counties; In South Africa |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Nov 18, 1899 |page=15 |quote= Howard Burnham of this city has been for a year or more the engineer of a gold mine near Johannesburg, South Africa and his wife has been with him.  Mrs. Burnham retreated to Cape Town at the start of the Second Boer War, but Howard remained at his post in the mines, protected by his American citizenship.}}</ref> While in the Transvaal, Burnham was a chief chemist, an engineer, and an assistant inspector for mines, and he wrote a textbook: ''Modern Mine Valuation''.<ref name=\"howardburnham\">{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=M. Howard |authorlink=Howard Burnham |title=Modern Mine Valuation |url=https://archive.org/details/modernminevaluat00burnuoft |publisher=London, C. Griffin and Company, limited |year=1912 |isbn= 1-151-74631-2}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Second Boer War]] broke out in 1899, Burnham felt he would be protected because of his American citizenship. Initially he remained at his post in the mines in the Boer Republic, but as a precaution he sent his wife to [[Cape Town, South Africa]], then a British colony.<ref name=\"latimes18nov1899\"/> But the situation in Johannesburg quickly worsened.  The Boers seized the mine and began working it for their own benefit.  Burnham traveled to [[East London, South Africa]] to inform the syndicate directors of the situation.  He was captured by the British and held 24 hrs before he could prove that he was an American citizen.  When he started back to Johannesburg, he was captured by the Boers who took him for a British spy.  For a time he was uncertain if he would be shot or hanged. He wired his family for funds to help get him out of his predicament.<ref name=\"sfcall17jan1900\"/><ref name=\"latimes17nov1900\">{{cite news |title= Southern California by Towns and Counties; A Pasadenan in Africa |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |issn= 0458-3035 |date= Jan 17, 1900 |page=I15 }}</ref> Only weeks earlier, his brother had been prospecting in [[Alaska]] during the [[Klondike Gold Rush]] when he received a telegram from [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Lord Roberts]] requesting his assistance in the war \u2013 Fred left for Africa within the hour.<ref name=\"americanheritage\">{{cite journal |author=Byron Farwell |authorlink=Byron Farwell |date=March 1976 |title=Taking Sides in the Boer War |journal=American Heritage Magazine |volume=20 |issue=3 |issn=0002-8738 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1976/3/1976_3_20.shtml |accessdate=2010-02-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107112133/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1976/3/1976_3_20.shtml |archivedate=2009-01-07 }}</ref> Fred Burnham had just been appointed Chief of Scouts for the [[British Army]] and was en route to South Africa via England, but he was still too distant to provide any immediate help.<ref name=\"scouting\"/>\n\nOver the next few years, he lived in both England and South Africa. He gave lectures and contributed a series of articles on mining techniques and the sundry principles underlying the finance of mining enterprises, more especially the \"risk rate.\"  In London on November 18, 1903, Burnham married Constance Newton, then a young school teacher and an heiress to [[Newton, Chambers & Company]], whom he had met on the ship during their voyage to South Africa.<ref>Marriage certificate, from Holly Trinity Church, Brompton Parish, London, 18th November 1903, column no. 118</ref> From 1905 until about 1908, Burnham was a non-resident fellow at the Royal Colonial Institute in London.<ref name=\"royalcolinst\">{{cite journal |author= |year=1908 |title=List of Fellows |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Colonial Institute |volume=39 |issue= |page=401}}</ref>\n\n== Mexico ==\n[[File:Burnham closeup 1900.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Maj [[Frederick Russell Burnham]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], brother]]\nWhile his wife and children stayed in England and France, Burnham returned to North America in 1907 and for the next few years became associated with the [[Yaqui River]] irrigation project in [[Mexico]] with his brother Fred.<ref name=\"scouting\"/> In 1908, he and W. A. Wadham of London, England, took a month-long geology and mining trip though Sonora on behalf of American and English business partners.<ref name=\"mining18july1908\">{{cite journal |journal=Mining and Engineering World |date=July 18, 1908 |volume=29 |issue= |page=110 |issn=0096-4840}}</ref> Negotiations were made for the purchase of four properties: the Batue, Mequite, La Fiera, and another property.  He considered the La Fiera to be the best of the lot and a small force of men under the supervision of John Anderson was put to work there.<ref name=\"mining18july1908\"/> In 1909, he traveled with Hector Walker of England on a 300-mile journey from [[Phoenix, Arizona]] into Mexico, and then east through [[Chihuahua, Chihuahua|Chihuahua]] and into the Sierra Madres to look for good grazing lands and minerals.<ref name=\"bisbeedailyreview_11sep1909\">{{cite news |title= Plan Extended Horseback Journal |newspaper= [[Bisbee Daily Review]] |location=[[Bisbee, Arizona]] |issn= 2158-4788 |date=Sep 11, 1909|page=1}}</ref>  His brother purchased water rights and some {{convert|300|acre|km2}} of land in this region and contacted an old friend of the Burnhams from Africa, [[John Hays Hammond]], who conducted his own studies and then purchased an additional {{convert|900000|acre|km2}} of this land\u2014an area the size of [[Rhode Island]].  Just as the irrigation and mining projects were nearing completion in 1912, a long series of [[Mexican Revolution|Mexican revolutions]] began.  The final blow to Burnham-Hammond plans came in 1917 when Mexico passed laws prohibiting the sale of land to foreigners. The Burnham and the Hammond families carried their properties until 1930 and then sold them to the Mexican government.<ref name=\"hammond\">{{cite book |author=[[John Hays Hammond]] |title=The Autobiography of John Hays Hammond |url=https://archive.org/details/autobiographyofj0001hamm |url-access=registration |publisher=Farrar & Rinehart|year=1935 |isbn= 0-405-05913-2 |page=565}}</ref>\n\n== World War I Espionage ==\nDuring [[World War I]], Burnham worked in intelligence for [[France]]. In 1914, he was incarcerated near [[Tampico, Mexico]] as a suspected spy, and was released with the help of [[William Jennings Bryan]], the U.S. Secretary of State.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">Mather Howard Burnham U.S. passport application affidavit/identifying documents, U.S. consulate, Barcelona, Spain, 26 February 1915</ref> He immediately left Mexico for France and stopped in [[Barcelona, Spain]] on his way to [[Algiers, Algeria]], then a French colony that the German Intelligence had infiltrated to support of the rebels.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> He was sent on a dangerous mission to lead 28 soldiers into the desert, meet with the rebels, and persuade them to make peace with the French.  On the way, the group encountered a hostile clan, lost 20 men, exhausted all of their ammunition, and were taken prisoner. All were executed, except Burnham. A sheik elder with the clan had earlier gotten into trouble with the French in Algiers and Burnham had come to his defense, leading to the release of the man.  Burnham returned to Algiers alone and was then sent to France.<ref name=\"chances\"/> \n \nIn 1917, [[List of intelligence agencies of France|French intelligence]] then sent Burnham across enemy lines as a spy to discover if the Germans were preparing a new front through the [[Alps]]. Traveling through neutral [[Switzerland]], Burnham assumed his former identity as an American mining engineer and crossed into Germany on the plea of extreme ill-health \u2013 his tuberculosis had violently resurfaced. Burnham had spent much time before the war in German spas, and his work for the French intelligence had been classified, so the real reason for his near-death return was not suspected by the authorities. Additionally, he was traveling with large quantities of American gold coins for his treatment and gold was desperately needed in wartime Germany. Nevertheless, Burnham was both searched and closely watched throughout his stay.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n \nWhile in Germany, Burnham applied his engineering skills to converting simple household materials in useful surveying instruments, and he used his wooden leg to conceal these tools when he traveled to places such as [[Bad Nauheim]]. Due to the high cost of his treatments, $500 a month paid in gold, Burnham was a welcome visitor at every resort in Germany.  Still, all of his correspondence was reviewed and at the insistence of German authorities he was frequently escorted by one or more nurses and a private secretary. Since he was unable to permanently record his surveys and other findings on paper, he relied on his remarkable memory.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n \nBurnham became very ill and was allowed to return to Switzerland for his health. The French government quickly transported Burnham to [[Cannes, France]]. From his death bed, Burnham shared his secrets with other intelligence officers and the French government transported his family from England to Cannes. The data Burnham had gathered was convincing: the Germans were not opening a new front in Alps and there was no need to move allied troops away from the Western Front.  His dying words he whispered to his surgeon: \"Always have I wanted to help pay the debt my country has owed to France. Go back to the front and save the living.  I am already dead.\" He was buried in Cannes beside the tomb of [[A. Kingsley Macomber]], another American, to honor the French Admiral [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Paul de Grasse]] whose fleet had enabled [[George Washington]] to force the surrender of [[Lord Cornwallis]] at [[Yorktown, Virginia]] in 1781.<ref name=\"chances\"/>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Fhcbabyfred.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Frederick Russell Burnham, M. Howard Burnham, Connie Burnham, and baby Fred, c1904]]\nBurnham was a descendant of [[Thomas Burnham]] (1617\u20131688) of [[Hartford, Connecticut]], the first American ancestor of a large number of Burnhams.<ref name=\"familyletters\"/> The descendants of Thomas Burnham have been noted in every American war, including the [[French and Indian war]].<ref name=\"pressreflib\">{{cite book |title =Press Reference Library: Notables of the West |publisher =International News Service |location=New York|year =1915 |oclc=5532411}}</ref>\n \nHe had four children:\n* Frederick Newton Burnham (Aug 25, 1904\u20131959), b. [[Lydenburg]], [[Republic of South Africa]] (now the Territory of South Africa). d. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n* Thomas Chambers Burnham (May 14, 1906 \u2013 2004), b. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]; d. [[Key Largo, Florida]].\n* Mary Burnham (May 29, 1909 \u2013 1987), b. [[Key Largo]], [[Florida]]; d. [[London, Connecticut]]\n* Katherine \"Kitty\" Burnham (October 9, 1911 \u2013 1999), b. [[San Francisco]], [[California]]; d. [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Works===\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |year=1901 |title=Continuous Section System Mine Sampling |journal=Transactions of the Institution of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=X |issue= |pages=204\u2013218 |issn=0371-7836}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |year=1904 |title=Treatment of Telluride Ores by Dry Crushing and Roasting at Kalgoorlie |journal=Transactions of the Institution of Mining and Metallurgy |volume=XIII |issue= |page=59 |issn=0371-7836}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Burnham |first=M. H. |date=June 1911 |title=Financing a Mine |journal=Mining Magazine |volume= |issue= |pages=445 |issn=0308-6631 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=M. Howard |title=Modern Mine Valuation |url=https://archive.org/details/modernminevaluat00burnrich |publisher=London, C. Griffin and Company, limited |year=1912 |isbn= 1-151-74631-2}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bradford |first=Mary E |author2=Richard H Bradford |title=An American family on the African frontier: the Burnham family letters, 1893\u20131896 |publisher=Roberts Rinehart|year=1993 |location=Niwot, Colorado|isbn= 1-879373-66-1}}  Some Burnham correspondence between 1893-1896.\n\n===Biographies===\n*{{cite book |last=Burnham |first=Frederick Russell |title=Taking Chances |publisher=Haynes |year=1944 |isbn= 1-879356-32-5}}.  Chapter XXXI is on M. Howard Burnham.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burnham, Mather Howard}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:American explorers]]\n[[Category:French spies]]\n[[Category:People from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:American mining businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American mining engineers]]\n[[Category:South African mining engineers]]\n[[Category:World War I spies for France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Michigan Technological University alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:19th-century South African engineers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Burnham"}
{"title_page": "The Great Train Robbery (2013 TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Great Train Robbery\n| image                    = The Great Train Robbery 2013 DVD.jpg\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]]\n| writer                   = [[Chris Chibnall]]\n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = \n| director                 = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Julian Jarrold]]\n* [[James Strong (director)|James Strong]] }}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Luke Evans]]\n* [[Jim Broadbent]]\n* [[Paul Anderson (actor)|Paul Anderson]] \n* Jack Roth\n* [[Martin Compston]] \n* [[Neil Maskell]] \n* [[Del Synnott]]\n* [[Nicholas Murchie]]\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Paul Englishby]]\n* [[Glenn Gregory]] }}\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 2\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| producer                 = Julia Stannard\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist |\n*Mark Eckersley\n*Billy Sneddon }}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist |\n*George Richmond\n*Gary Shaw }}\n| runtime                  = 90 minutes\n| company                  = [[World Productions]]\n| distributor              = Kew Media\n| budget                   = \n| network                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[16:9]] ([[1080i]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = 18\n| last_aired               = 19 December 2013\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03mk394\n| website_title            = BBC Website\n| production_website       = https://www.world-productions.com/productions/the-great-train-robbery\n}}\n\n'''''The Great Train Robbery''''' is a two-part British [[television]] miniseries,<ref name=\"MP\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/greattrainrobbery/ | title=The Great Train Robbery - Chris Chibnall's thrilling new drama for BBC One | work=BBC | date=18 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> written by [[Chris Chibnall]], that was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 18 and 19 December 2013.  The series is distributed worldwide by Kew Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-productions.com/productions/the-great-train-robbery|title=The Great Train Robbery - World Productions|last=Productions|first=World|website=World Productions|language=en|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> \n\nIt tells the story of the [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]] on 8 August 1963, first from the perspective of the robbers, and then from the perspective of the police. Episode one, ''A Robber's Tale'' details the organisation of and successful completion of the robbery. Episode two, ''A Copper's Tale'' follows the police investigation into the crime and subsequent arrest of many of the perpetrators.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2013/51/the-great-train-robbery-a-robbers-tale.html|title=The Great Train Robbery \u2013 A Robber's Tale|date=18 December 2013|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Coincidentally, the first part, ''A Robber's Tale'', was shown on the same day that train robber [[Ronnie Biggs]] died.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/ronnie-biggs-dead-great-train-robber-dies-aged-84-9012029.html | title=Ronnie Biggs dead: Great Train Robbery fugitive dies aged 84 | work=The Independent | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=18 December 2013 | author=Withnall, Adam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/dec/18/ronnie-biggs-picks-moment-great-train-robbery | title=Ronnie Biggs picks his moment one last time | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Campbell, Duncan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/dec/18/ronnie-biggs-face-great-train-robbery | title=Ronnie Biggs, face of Great Train Robbery, slips away with perfect timing | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Campbell, Duncan}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''A Robber's Tale'' is set between November 1962 and the aftermath of the [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]] on 8 August 1963. Beginning at [[London Heathrow Airport]] where the big practice robbery took place, [[Bruce Reynolds]] ([[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]]) gathered a group of men to target the Royal Mail train heading between [[Glasgow]] and London.<ref name=\"MP\" />\n\n''A Copper's Tale'' begins in the early morning of 8 August 1963 after the [[train robbery]] took place. Six of the best police officers from [[Scotland Yard]] are called to help with the investigation, with DCS [[Tommy Butler]] ([[Jim Broadbent]]) in charge.<ref name=\"MP\" />\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Great Train Robbery 2013.jpg|thumbnail|The cast of \"A Robber's Tale\"]]\n[[File:The Great Train Robbery 2013 cops.jpg|thumbnail|The cast of \"A Copper's Tale\"]]\n\n* [[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]] as [[Bruce Reynolds]]\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as DCS [[Tommy Butler]]\n* [[Paul Anderson (actor)|Paul Anderson]] as [[Gordon Goody]]\n* Jack Roth as Charlie Wilson\n* [[Martin Compston]] as Roy James\n* [[Neil Maskell]] as [[Buster Edwards]]\n* [[Del Synnott]] as [[Brian Field]]\n* [[Nicholas Murchie]] as Roger Cordery\n* Jordan Long as [[Tommy Wisbey]]\n* Jack Gordon as [[Ronnie Biggs]]\n* George Ward as [[Nick Reynolds]]\n* [[Eric Hulme]] as [[Jack Mills]]\n* [[James Bye (actor)|James Bye]] as [[John Daly (Great Train Robbery)|John Daly]]\n* [[Robert Glenister]] as DI Frank Williams \n* Bethany Muir as Franny Reynolds\n*Olivia K Williams as Daughter of Charlie Wilson\n\n===A Robber's Tale===\n* [[John Voce]] as Billy Still\n* [[Bill Thomas (actor)|Bill Thomas]] as Alf\n* Nigel Collins as Bert Turner\n* [[Dean Smith (actor)|Dean Smith]] as David Whitby\n* Mark Stratton as Mr. Wyatt\n\n===A Copper's Tale===\n* [[Ken Bones]] as Com. George Hatherill \n* [[Richard Hope (actor)|Richard Hope]] as [[Malcolm Fewtrell|DCS Malcolm Fewtrell]] \n* [[George Costigan]] as DCS Ernie Millen \n* [[John Salthouse]] as DCI Sid Bradbury \n* [[Tim Pigott-Smith]] as DS Maurice Ray \n* [[Nick Moran]] as [[Jack Slipper|DS Jack Slipper]]\n* [[Tom Chambers (actor)|Tom Chambers]] as DS Steve Moore\n* Matthew Jure as DS Stanley Davies \n* James McGregor as DC Tommy Thorburn\n* Tommy McDonnell as DC Keith Milner \n* Tom Beard as Dr. Ian Holden\n* Christine Cox as Emily Clarke \n* [[Gwyneth Strong]] as Dorothy \n* [[James Wilby]] as [[John Denby Wheater]|John Wheater] \n* [[James Fox]] as Henry Brooke\n\n==Production==\n''The Great Train Robbery'' was commissioned by [[Ben Stephenson]], controller of BBC Drama, and [[Danny Cohen (television executive)|Danny Cohen]], controller of BBC One.<ref name=\"BBC2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/broadbent-cast-gtr.html | title=Jim Broadbent to lead cast in film two of BBC One's The Great Train Robbery | work=BBC | date=2 May 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/great-train-robbery.html | title=Cast announced for first film of BBC One's The Great Train Robbery | work=BBC | date=6 March 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> The [[executive producer]]s are Simon Heath for [[World Productions]], the company behind the series, and Polly Hill for the [[BBC]].<ref name=\"BBC1\" /> Julia Stannard is the producer of the two ninety-minute films.<ref name=\"BBC1\" />\n\nThe two films were first due to be broadcast in August 2013, on the 50th anniversary of the train robbery, but was postponed to December 2013 because of scheduling issues.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/10784895.Great_Train_Robbery_drama_filmed_in_Yorkshire/ | title=Great Train Robbery drama filmed in Yorkshire | work=York Press | date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013 | author=Branagan, Mark}}</ref> The production was inspired by the book ''Signal Red'' by [[Robert Ryan (writer)|Robert Ryan]].\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in Yorkshire in March 2013.<ref name=\"BBC1\" /> Various parts of [[Leeds city centre]] were used, such as the Adelphi public house, [[the Calls]], [[Briggate, Leeds|Briggate]], [[Hyde Park Picture House, Leeds|Hyde Park Picture House]] and other parts of [[Hyde Park, Leeds|Hyde Park]].<ref name=\"YP\">{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/general-news/great-film-robbery-as-yorkshire-blags-bbc-rail-drama-1-6211587 | title=Great film robbery as Yorkshire blags BBC rail drama | work=Yorkshire Post | date=4 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> The [[Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]] was used as Sears Crossing, where the actual robbery took place.<ref name=\"YP\" /> Other scenes were filmed at [[Bradford]], [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[Haworth]] and [[Goole]].<ref name=\"YP\" /> [[Filey]] was used instead of [[Torquay]] for the scenes involving Reynolds' hideout.<ref name=\"YP\" /> According to the BBC, Yorkshire is the \"most cost-effective and realistic alternative\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/great-train-robbery-tv-drama-films-in-unspoiled-yorkshire-to-get-back-to-the-60s-8919962.html | title=Great Train Robbery TV drama films in unspoiled Yorkshire to get back to the 60s | work=The Independent | date=3 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013 | author=Foot, Tom}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" width=\"100%\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| #\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Title\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Directed by\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Written by\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Original air date\n! style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\" | UK viewers<br />(millions)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-top-30 | title=BARB Top 30s}}</ref>\n|-\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=A Robber's Tale\n |DirectedBy=[[Julian Jarrold]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Chris Chibnall]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|18|df=yes}}\n |Aux4=6.35\n |ShortSummary=After a heist at London Heathrow Airport garners a disappointing haul, [[Bruce Reynolds]] and his gang of working-class, small-time crooks get a tip about the [[Royal Mail]] train. The daily train coming from [[Glasgow]] on the [[West Coast Main Line]] will be carrying sacks of excess currency and picking up more at each stop on its way to [[London]]. They believe up to \u00a31 million will be on board by the time it passes through [[Buckinghamshire]]. They bring in two train experts to join the crew and plot the heist from a rented farmhouse in the [[Aylesbury Vale]], where they plan to hide out for a week until things calm down. But when the heist nets a record score of more than \u00a32.6 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|2.6|1963}} million today), Reynolds knows the police will be hot on their trail.\n |LineColor=bfe0bf\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=A Copper's Tale\n |DirectedBy=[[James Strong (director)|James Strong]]\n |WrittenBy=Chris Chibnall\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|19|df=yes}}\n |Aux4=5.99\n |ShortSummary= Four days after the biggest robbery in British history to date, [[Flying Squad]] Chief Superintendent [[Tommy Butler]] is brought in to lead the investigation by the [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor |Home Secretary]]. Though the heist occurred in Buckinghamshire, Butler is convinced it was organised by London criminals, and he compiles his own dream team of detectives to hunt them down. They come up with shortlists of suspects among known criminals and [[Bruce Reynolds]] is on that list. A \u00a310,000 reward for information leads to a tip from a neighbour about the rented farmhouse, but they are soon drowning in hoax callers and fake tips. Informants help them track down and arrest the gang one by one until three years after the robbery, when only one man is still at large: Bruce Reynolds.\n |LineColor=bfe0bf\n}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''Cheshire Today'', the BBC was criticised for glorifying criminals when it announced the series.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cheshire-today.co.uk/22835/bbc-launch-great-train-robbery-drama/ | title=BBC launch Great Train Robbery drama | work=Cheshire Today | date=20 November 2013 | accessdate=23 November 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001821/http://www.cheshire-today.co.uk/22835/bbc-launch-great-train-robbery-drama/ | archivedate=3 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nOvernight figures showed that ''A Robber's Tale'', the first episode of ''The Great Train Robbery'', was watched by 23.2% of the viewing audience for that time, with 5.23 million watching it.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/great-train-robbery-makes-solid-start/5064892.article | title=Great Train Robbery makes solid start | work=Broadcast Now | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Parker, Robin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a539423/great-train-robbery-drama-tops-wednesday-with-52-million.html | title=Great Train Robbery drama tops Wednesday with 5.2 million | work=Digital Spy | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=20 December 2013 | author=Eames, Tom}}</ref> The second episode, ''A Copper's Tale'', had a 23.1% audience share and 4.95 million viewers, according to overnight figures.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a539793/great-train-robbery-concludes-with-49-million-on-bbc-one.html | title=Great Train Robbery concludes with 4.9 million on BBC One | work=Digital Spy | date=20 December 2013 | accessdate=20 December 2013 | author=Eames, Tom}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''A Robber's Tale'' received a mixed response. ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' journalist Keith Watson gave the film two stars out of five and said he would have liked to have seen more background on the gang members.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/12/19/the-bbcs-the-great-train-robbery-an-unmerited-attempt-to-lend-the-crime-a-noble-quality-4235997/ | title=The BBC\u2019s The Great Train Robbery: An unmerited attempt to lend the crime a noble quality | work=Metro | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Watson, Keith}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''{{'s}} Tom Rowley gave it four stars out of five and noted the high attention to detail by [[Chris Chibnall]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10526449/The-Great-Train-Robbery-A-Robbers-Tale-BBC-One-review.html | title=The Great Train Robbery: A Robber's Tale, BBC One, review | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Rowley, Tom}}</ref> Sam Wollaston from ''[[The Guardian]]'' said ''A Robber's Tale'' \"beautifully explores the dynamic of a gang of men\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/dec/18/the-great-train-robbery-bbc-tv-review-biggs | title=The Great Train Robbery \u2013 TV review | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Wollaston, Sam}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n''The Great Train Robbery'' received a [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] nomination in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/10749461/Helena-Bonham-Carter-up-for-TV-Bafta-for-role-of-Elizabeth-Taylor.html | title=Helena Bonham Carter up for TV Bafta for role of Elizabeth Taylor | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Furness, Hannah}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/baftas/10749101/Bafta-TV-Awards-2014-the-nominations.html | title=Bafta TV Awards 2014: the nominations | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Lawrence, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bafta-tv-awards-2014-nominations-in-full-9243165.html | title=Bafta TV awards 2014: Nominations in full | work=The Independent | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Denham, Jess}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a562750/bafta-television-awards-2014-this-years-nominees-in-full.html | title=BAFTA Television Awards 2014: This year's nominees in full | work=Digital Spy | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Harris, Jamie}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe two films have been released on DVD by publisher [[Acorn Media UK]] and is available from the [[BBC]]. It was released at other outlets on 6 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbcshop.com/drama+arts/the-great-train-robbery-a-coppers-tale+a-robbers-tale-dvd/invt/av3129 | title=The Great Train Robbery: A Coppers Tale & A Robbers Tale (DVD) | work=BBC Shop | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt2763296}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{Radio Times|programme/cqyzm2/the-great-train-robbery|title=''The Great Train Robbery''}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/greattrainrobbery/chris-chibnall.html Interview with Chris Chibnall about ''The Great Train Robbery'']\n\n{{Great Train Robbery (1963)}}\n{{Chris Chibnall}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great Train Robbery (TV series), The}}\n[[Category:2013 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2013 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British television miniseries]] \n[[Category:BBC crime drama television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC television miniseries]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1963]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Chris Chibnall]]\n[[Category:Great Train Robbery (1963)|2013 TV]]\n[[Category:Robbery in television]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Great Train Robbery\n| image                    = The Great Train Robbery 2013 DVD.jpg\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]]\n| writer                   = [[Chris Chibnall]]\n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = \n| director                 = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Julian Jarrold]]\n* [[James Strong (director)|James Strong]] }}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Luke Evans]]\n* [[Jim Broadbent]]\n* [[Paul Anderson (actor)|Paul Anderson]] \n* Jack Roth\n* [[Martin Compston]] \n* [[Neil Maskell]] \n* [[Del Synnott]]\n* [[Nicholas Murchie]]\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Paul Englishby]]\n* [[Glenn Gregory]] }}\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 2\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| producer                 = Julia Stannard\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist |\n*Mark Eckersley\n*Billy Sneddon }}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist |\n*George Richmond\n*Gary Shaw }}\n| runtime                  = 90 minutes\n| company                  = [[World Productions]]\n| distributor              = Kew Media\n| budget                   = \n| network                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[16:9]] ([[1080i]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = 18\n| last_aired               = 19 December 2013\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03mk394\n| website_title            = BBC Website\n| production_website       = https://www.world-productions.com/productions/the-great-train-robbery\n}}\n\n'''''The Great Train Robbery''''' is a two-part British [[television]] miniseries,<ref name=\"MP\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/greattrainrobbery/ | title=The Great Train Robbery - Chris Chibnall's thrilling new drama for BBC One | work=BBC | date=18 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> written by [[Chris Chibnall]], that was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 18 and 19 December 2013.  The series is distributed worldwide by Kew Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-productions.com/productions/the-great-train-robbery|title=The Great Train Robbery - World Productions|last=Productions|first=World|website=World Productions|language=en|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> \n\nIt tells the story of the [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]] on 8 August 1963, first from the perspective of the robbers, and then from the perspective of the police. Episode one, ''A Robber's Tale'' details the organisation of and successful completion of the robbery. Episode two, ''A Copper's Tale'' follows the police investigation into the crime and subsequent arrest of many of the perpetrators.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2013/51/the-great-train-robbery-a-robbers-tale.html|title=The Great Train Robbery \u2013 A Robber's Tale|date=18 December 2013|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Coincidentally, the first part, ''A Robber's Tale'', was shown on the same day that train robber [[Ronnie Biggs]] died.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/ronnie-biggs-dead-great-train-robber-dies-aged-84-9012029.html | title=Ronnie Biggs dead: Great Train Robbery fugitive dies aged 84 | work=The Independent | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=18 December 2013 | author=Withnall, Adam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/dec/18/ronnie-biggs-picks-moment-great-train-robbery | title=Ronnie Biggs picks his moment one last time | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Campbell, Duncan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/dec/18/ronnie-biggs-face-great-train-robbery | title=Ronnie Biggs, face of Great Train Robbery, slips away with perfect timing | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Campbell, Duncan}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''A Robber's Tale'' is set between November 1962 and the aftermath of the [[Great Train Robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]] on 8 August 1963. Beginning at [[London Heathrow Airport]] where the big practice robbery took place, [[Bruce Reynolds]] ([[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]]) gathered a group of men to target the Royal Mail train heading between [[Glasgow]] and London.<ref name=\"MP\" />\n\n''A Copper's Tale'' begins in the early morning of 8 August 1963 after the [[train robbery]] took place. Six of the best police officers from [[Scotland Yard]] are called to help with the investigation, with DCS [[Tommy Butler]] ([[Jim Broadbent]]) in charge.<ref name=\"MP\" />\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Great Train Robbery 2013.jpg|thumbnail|The cast of \"A Robber's Tale\"]]\n[[File:The Great Train Robbery 2013 cops.jpg|thumbnail|The cast of \"A Copper's Tale\"]]\n\n* [[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]] as [[Bruce Reynolds]]\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as DCS [[Tommy Butler]]\n* [[Paul Anderson (actor)|Paul Anderson]] as [[Gordon Goody]]\n* Jack Roth as Charlie Wilson\n* [[Martin Compston]] as Roy James\n* [[Neil Maskell]] as [[Buster Edwards]]\n* [[Del Synnott]] as [[Brian Field]]\n* [[Nicholas Murchie]] as Roger Cordery\n* Jordan Long as [[Tommy Wisbey]]\n* Jack Gordon as [[Ronnie Biggs]]\n* George Ward as [[Nick Reynolds]]\n* [[Eric Hulme]] as [[Jack Mills]]\n* [[James Bye (actor)|James Bye]] as [[John Daly (Great Train Robbery)|John Daly]]\n* [[Robert Glenister]] as DI Frank Williams \n* Bethany Muir as Franny Reynolds\n*Olivia K Williams as Daughter of Charlie Wilson\n\n===A Robber's Tale===\n* [[John Voce]] as Billy Still\n* [[Bill Thomas (actor)|Bill Thomas]] as Alf\n* Nigel Collins as Bert Turner\n* [[Dean Smith (actor)|Dean Smith]] as David Whitby\n* Mark Stratton as Mr. Wyatt\n\n===A Copper's Tale===\n* [[Ken Bones]] as Com. George Hatherill \n* [[Richard Hope (actor)|Richard Hope]] as [[Malcolm Fewtrell|DCS Malcolm Fewtrell]] \n* [[George Costigan]] as DCS Ernie Millen \n* [[John Salthouse]] as DCI Sid Bradbury \n* [[Tim Pigott-Smith]] as DS Maurice Ray \n* [[Nick Moran]] as [[Jack Slipper|DS Jack Slipper]]\n* [[Tom Chambers (actor)|Tom Chambers]] as DS Steve Moore\n* Matthew Jure as DS Stanley Davies \n* James McGregor as DC Tommy Thorburn\n* Tommy McDonnell as DC Keith Milner \n* Tom Beard as Dr. Ian Holden\n* Christine Cox as Emily Clarke \n* [[Gwyneth Strong]] as Dorothy \n* [[James Wilby]] as [[John Wheater]] \n* [[James Fox]] as Henry Brooke\n\n==Production==\n''The Great Train Robbery'' was commissioned by [[Ben Stephenson]], controller of BBC Drama, and [[Danny Cohen (television executive)|Danny Cohen]], controller of BBC One.<ref name=\"BBC2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/broadbent-cast-gtr.html | title=Jim Broadbent to lead cast in film two of BBC One's The Great Train Robbery | work=BBC | date=2 May 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/great-train-robbery.html | title=Cast announced for first film of BBC One's The Great Train Robbery | work=BBC | date=6 March 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> The [[executive producer]]s are Simon Heath for [[World Productions]], the company behind the series, and Polly Hill for the [[BBC]].<ref name=\"BBC1\" /> Julia Stannard is the producer of the two ninety-minute films.<ref name=\"BBC1\" />\n\nThe two films were first due to be broadcast in August 2013, on the 50th anniversary of the train robbery, but was postponed to December 2013 because of scheduling issues.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/10784895.Great_Train_Robbery_drama_filmed_in_Yorkshire/ | title=Great Train Robbery drama filmed in Yorkshire | work=York Press | date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013 | author=Branagan, Mark}}</ref> The production was inspired by the book ''Signal Red'' by [[Robert Ryan (writer)|Robert Ryan]].\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in Yorkshire in March 2013.<ref name=\"BBC1\" /> Various parts of [[Leeds city centre]] were used, such as the Adelphi public house, [[the Calls]], [[Briggate, Leeds|Briggate]], [[Hyde Park Picture House, Leeds|Hyde Park Picture House]] and other parts of [[Hyde Park, Leeds|Hyde Park]].<ref name=\"YP\">{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/general-news/great-film-robbery-as-yorkshire-blags-bbc-rail-drama-1-6211587 | title=Great film robbery as Yorkshire blags BBC rail drama | work=Yorkshire Post | date=4 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> The [[Keighley and Worth Valley Railway]] was used as Sears Crossing, where the actual robbery took place.<ref name=\"YP\" /> Other scenes were filmed at [[Bradford]], [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[Haworth]] and [[Goole]].<ref name=\"YP\" /> [[Filey]] was used instead of [[Torquay]] for the scenes involving Reynolds' hideout.<ref name=\"YP\" /> According to the BBC, Yorkshire is the \"most cost-effective and realistic alternative\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/great-train-robbery-tv-drama-films-in-unspoiled-yorkshire-to-get-back-to-the-60s-8919962.html | title=Great Train Robbery TV drama films in unspoiled Yorkshire to get back to the 60s | work=The Independent | date=3 November 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013 | author=Foot, Tom}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" width=\"100%\" style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| #\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Title\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Directed by\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Written by\n!style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\"| Original air date\n! style=\"background: #bfe0bf;\" | UK viewers<br />(millions)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-top-30 | title=BARB Top 30s}}</ref>\n|-\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=A Robber's Tale\n |DirectedBy=[[Julian Jarrold]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Chris Chibnall]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|18|df=yes}}\n |Aux4=6.35\n |ShortSummary=After a heist at London Heathrow Airport garners a disappointing haul, [[Bruce Reynolds]] and his gang of working-class, small-time crooks get a tip about the [[Royal Mail]] train. The daily train coming from [[Glasgow]] on the [[West Coast Main Line]] will be carrying sacks of excess currency and picking up more at each stop on its way to [[London]]. They believe up to \u00a31 million will be on board by the time it passes through [[Buckinghamshire]]. They bring in two train experts to join the crew and plot the heist from a rented farmhouse in the [[Aylesbury Vale]], where they plan to hide out for a week until things calm down. But when the heist nets a record score of more than \u00a32.6 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|2.6|1963}} million today), Reynolds knows the police will be hot on their trail.\n |LineColor=bfe0bf\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=A Copper's Tale\n |DirectedBy=[[James Strong (director)|James Strong]]\n |WrittenBy=Chris Chibnall\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2013|12|19|df=yes}}\n |Aux4=5.99\n |ShortSummary= Four days after the biggest robbery in British history to date, [[Flying Squad]] Chief Superintendent [[Tommy Butler]] is brought in to lead the investigation by the [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor |Home Secretary]]. Though the heist occurred in Buckinghamshire, Butler is convinced it was organised by London criminals, and he compiles his own dream team of detectives to hunt them down. They come up with shortlists of suspects among known criminals and [[Bruce Reynolds]] is on that list. A \u00a310,000 reward for information leads to a tip from a neighbour about the rented farmhouse, but they are soon drowning in hoax callers and fake tips. Informants help them track down and arrest the gang one by one until three years after the robbery, when only one man is still at large: Bruce Reynolds.\n |LineColor=bfe0bf\n}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''Cheshire Today'', the BBC was criticised for glorifying criminals when it announced the series.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cheshire-today.co.uk/22835/bbc-launch-great-train-robbery-drama/ | title=BBC launch Great Train Robbery drama | work=Cheshire Today | date=20 November 2013 | accessdate=23 November 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001821/http://www.cheshire-today.co.uk/22835/bbc-launch-great-train-robbery-drama/ | archivedate=3 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nOvernight figures showed that ''A Robber's Tale'', the first episode of ''The Great Train Robbery'', was watched by 23.2% of the viewing audience for that time, with 5.23 million watching it.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/great-train-robbery-makes-solid-start/5064892.article | title=Great Train Robbery makes solid start | work=Broadcast Now | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Parker, Robin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a539423/great-train-robbery-drama-tops-wednesday-with-52-million.html | title=Great Train Robbery drama tops Wednesday with 5.2 million | work=Digital Spy | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=20 December 2013 | author=Eames, Tom}}</ref> The second episode, ''A Copper's Tale'', had a 23.1% audience share and 4.95 million viewers, according to overnight figures.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a539793/great-train-robbery-concludes-with-49-million-on-bbc-one.html | title=Great Train Robbery concludes with 4.9 million on BBC One | work=Digital Spy | date=20 December 2013 | accessdate=20 December 2013 | author=Eames, Tom}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''A Robber's Tale'' received a mixed response. ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' journalist Keith Watson gave the film two stars out of five and said he would have liked to have seen more background on the gang members.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/12/19/the-bbcs-the-great-train-robbery-an-unmerited-attempt-to-lend-the-crime-a-noble-quality-4235997/ | title=The BBC\u2019s The Great Train Robbery: An unmerited attempt to lend the crime a noble quality | work=Metro | date=19 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Watson, Keith}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''{{'s}} Tom Rowley gave it four stars out of five and noted the high attention to detail by [[Chris Chibnall]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10526449/The-Great-Train-Robbery-A-Robbers-Tale-BBC-One-review.html | title=The Great Train Robbery: A Robber's Tale, BBC One, review | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Rowley, Tom}}</ref> Sam Wollaston from ''[[The Guardian]]'' said ''A Robber's Tale'' \"beautifully explores the dynamic of a gang of men\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/dec/18/the-great-train-robbery-bbc-tv-review-biggs | title=The Great Train Robbery \u2013 TV review | work=The Guardian | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author=Wollaston, Sam}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n''The Great Train Robbery'' received a [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] nomination in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/10749461/Helena-Bonham-Carter-up-for-TV-Bafta-for-role-of-Elizabeth-Taylor.html | title=Helena Bonham Carter up for TV Bafta for role of Elizabeth Taylor | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Furness, Hannah}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/baftas/10749101/Bafta-TV-Awards-2014-the-nominations.html | title=Bafta TV Awards 2014: the nominations | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Lawrence, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bafta-tv-awards-2014-nominations-in-full-9243165.html | title=Bafta TV awards 2014: Nominations in full | work=The Independent | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Denham, Jess}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a562750/bafta-television-awards-2014-this-years-nominees-in-full.html | title=BAFTA Television Awards 2014: This year's nominees in full | work=Digital Spy | date=7 April 2014 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | author=Harris, Jamie}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe two films have been released on DVD by publisher [[Acorn Media UK]] and is available from the BBC. It was released at other outlets on 6 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbcshop.com/drama+arts/the-great-train-robbery-a-coppers-tale+a-robbers-tale-dvd/invt/av3129 | title=The Great Train Robbery: A Coppers Tale & A Robbers Tale (DVD) | work=BBC Shop | accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt2763296}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{Radio Times|programme/cqyzm2/the-great-train-robbery|title=''The Great Train Robbery''}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/greattrainrobbery/chris-chibnall.html Interview with Chris Chibnall about ''The Great Train Robbery'']\n\n{{Great Train Robbery (1963)}}\n{{Chris Chibnall}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great Train Robbery (TV series), The}}\n[[Category:2013 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2013 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British television miniseries]] \n[[Category:BBC crime drama television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC television miniseries]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1963]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Chris Chibnall]]\n[[Category:Great Train Robbery (1963)|2013 TV]]\n[[Category:Robbery in television]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in England]]\n", "name_user": "Jpbowen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link update, tidying", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Great_Train_Robbery_(2013_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Shiv Ganga Express", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{ Infobox rail service\n| name= Shiv Ganga Express \u0936\u093f\u0935 \u0917\u0902\u0917\u093e \u090f\u0915\u094d\u0938\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\n| image= 12560 Shiv Ganga Express - Train board.jpg\n| caption= \n| type= [[Superfast/Mail Trains in India|Superfast]]\n| State= [[Delhi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| first=1 July 2002\n| last=\n| operator=[[North Eastern Railway zone|North Eastern Railway]]\n| start= [[Manduadih railway station|Manduadih]]'''(MUV)'''\n| stops= 2\n| end=[[New Delhi Railway Station|New Delhi]]'''(NDLS)'''\n| distance= {{convert|755|km|miles}}\n| journeytime= 11 hours 55 minutes\n| frequency = Daily\n| class=  AC-I, AC-II, AC-III, SL, General\n| seating=Yes\n| sleeping=Yes\n| catering= Available (paid)\n| gauge= {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on|allk=on}}\n| trainnumber = 12559 / 12560\n| speed= Maximum {{convert|110|kph|mph}}\nAverage={{convert|63|kph|mph}} (inuding halts),\n{{convert|62|kph|mph}} (excluding halts)\n| map = [[File:Shiv Ganga Express (New Delhi - Varanasi) Route map.jpg|250px]]\n}}\n'''Shiv Ganga Express''' ('''\u0936\u093f\u0935 \u0917\u0902\u0917\u093e \u090f\u0915\u094d\u0938\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938''') is a [[Superfast/Mail Trains in India|Superfast]] train of [[North Eastern Railway Zone]] named after the two jewels of [[Varanasi]]: [[Shiva]] and the [[Ganges]] river. The main towns along the route are [[Prayagraj]] and [[Kanpur]].It was passed in 2002's [[Railway Budget]] and hence initiated its journey from 1 July 2002. It operates daily and covers a distance of {{convert|755|km|mi}} from [[Manduadih railway station|Manduadih]] to [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]]. Shiv Ganga Express originally consisted of 24 [[ICF Coaches]] which includes 1 First AC coach, 1 Second AC coach, 4 Third AC coach, 10 Sleeper Class coaches,5 General (Un-Reserved) coaches, Pantry Car and 2 SLR overall 24 coaches that makes it one of the longest trains in India. Shiv Ganga Express is usually hauled by a [[WAP 4]] or a [[WAP 7]] Locomotive from [[Manduadih railway station|Manduadih]] to [[New Delhi Railway Station|New Delhi]]. It is considered as the best train between [[New Delhi]] and [[Varanasi]]. It has got a maximum speed of {{convert|110|kph|mph}}. It is one of the few [[Superfast/Mail Trains in India|Superfast]] trains which pass through [[Manduadih-Madho Singh-Allahabad]] section. This train is now running with 22 [[LHB Coaches]] from 16 June 2015 which includes 1 First AC Coach (H1), 1 Second AC Coach (A1), 4 Third AC Coaches (B1-B4), 9 Sleeper Class Coaches (S1-S9), 4 General (Un-Reserved) Coaches, Pantry Car and 2 EOG (End-on Generator).\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - EOG.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express \u2013 EOG\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - Sleeper Class coach with Prayagraj Kumbh 2019 decal.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - Sleeper Class coach with [[Prayagraj Kumbh 2019]] decal\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - Pantry Car coach with Prayagraj Kumbh 2019 decal.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - Pantry Car coach with [[Prayagraj Kumbh 2019]] decal\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 3 tier coach with Prayagraj Kumbh 2019 decal.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 3 tier coach with [[Prayagraj Kumbh 2019]] decal\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 2 tier coach with Prayagraj Kumbh 2019 decal.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 2 tier coach with [[Prayagraj Kumbh 2019]] decal\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 1st Class coach with Prayagraj Kumbh 2019 decal.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - AC 1st Class coach with [[Prayagraj Kumbh 2019]] decal\nFile:12560 Shiv Ganga Express - EOG with Kanpur based WAP 4.jpg|12560 Shiv Ganga Express - EOG with [[Kanpur Central|Kanpur]] based [[WAP 4]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Time Table==\n<br />\n'''From Varanasi New Delhi it starts with Number 12559 and time table is as:\n<br/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No. !! Station !! Arrival !! Departure !! Halt (Min.) !! Day !! Elevation\n|-\n|1 || [[Manduadih railway station|Manduadih]]  || Starting Station || 19:55 || - || 1 || 80m\n|-\n| 2 || [[Allahabad Junction railway station|Allahabad]] || 22:20 || 22:30 || 10 || 1 || 100m\n|-\n| 3 || [[Kanpur Central]] || 01:05 || 01:13 || 8 || 2 || 129m\n|-\n| 4 || [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] || 08:10 || Destination || - || 2 || 216m\n|}\n\n'''From New Delhi to Manduadih(Varanasi) it starts with Number 12560 and time table is as:\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No. !! Station !! Arrival !! Departure !! Halt (Min.) !! Day !! Elevation\n|-\n| 1 || [[New Delhi railway station|New Delhi]] || Starting Station || 18:55 || - || 1 || 216m\n|-\n| 2 || [[Kanpur Central]] || 01:00 || 01:05 || 5 || 2 || 129m\n|-\n| 3 || [[Allahabad Junction railway station|Allahabad]] || 03:50 || 04:00 || 10 || 2 || 100m\n|-\n| 4 || [[Manduadih railway station|Manduadih]] || 06:50 || Destination || - || 2 || 80m\n\n|}\n\n==Reservation==\nPeople have to take an advanced reservation ticket to travel in the train except for the General class.\nIt records a rush of passengers throughout the year in both peak as well as non-peak period.\nBecause of its time of departure and arrival, it runs fully packed, therefore it is considered as a [[VIP]] train or '''Purvanchal Rajdhani''' by [[Indian Railway]].\n\n==Coach composition==\n\nThis train has 22 coaches between Manduadih to New Delhi station.\n\n9 Sleeper class Coach (S1 to S9)<br>\n4 Sleeper 3 Tier AC Coach (B1 to B4)<br>\n1 1st Class AC Coach (H1)<br>\n1 AC 2 Tier Coach (A1)<br>\n4 General compartments (Unreserved)<br>\n1 Pantry Car<br>\n2 EOGs\n\nCoach composition for 12559 :\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"background:lightskyblue;\"| Loco\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"background:lightskyblue;\"| 1\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"background:lightsky